                    <div class="services-content-inner">
                        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs) about Squint Eye</h2>
                        <h3>Q1: Can a squint eye be corrected without surgery?</h3>
                        <p>Sometimes a squint eye can be corrected without surgery. Non-surgical treatment options such as eyeglasses or contact lenses, prism lenses, vision therapy, and patching can help manage and improve certain types of squint.</p>
                        <h3>Q2: What is the ideal age for squint eye treatment?</h3>
                        <p>The ideal age for squint eye treatment varies depending on the individual and the type of squint. Early intervention is generally recommended, and treatment can begin as early as infancy or childhood.</p>
                        <h3>Q3: Is squint eye hereditary?</h3>
                        <p>Yes, squint eyes can have a hereditary component. If parents or close relatives have a history of squint, there is an increased likelihood of it being passed on to their children.</p>
                        <h3>Q4: Will wearing glasses improve a squint?</h3>
                        <p>Wearing glasses can help improve a squint in cases where the misalignment is associated with refractive errors, such as nearsightedness, farsightedness, or astigmatism. The appropriate prescription lenses can correct the refractive error and improve visual clarity.</p>
